  "text": "Firefox crashes when processing CSS calc() with extreme values due to unhandled numeric overflow in the calc() expression resolution pipeline. The issue spans both the Rust-based Servo CSS parsing engine and the C++ Gecko layout system.\n\n**Parsing:** calc() expressions are parsed in servo/components/style/values/specified/calc.rs by the CalcNode::parse function, which accepts mathematical functions like min(), max(), clamp(), hypot(), etc. These functions support arbitrary numeric values without initial bounds checking.\n\n**Resolution:** The critical overflow occurs during value resolution:\n\n1. **Rust-side computation (servo/components/style/values/generics/calc.rs):** The CalcNode::resolve_internal function recursively resolves calc() expressions. For functions like hypot(), it performs v.powi(2) operations that can overflow to infinity when the input values are extreme (e.g., calc(hypot(1e100, 1e100))). The function applies operations without overflow detection:\n   - Line ~1153: result.map(|v| v.powi(2))? - First value squared\n   - Line ~1165: result.map(|v| v + child_value.powi(2))? - Sum of squares\n   - Line ~1168: result.map(|v| v.sqrt())? - Square root\n\n2. **Computed value resolution (servo/components/style/values/computed/length_percentage.rs):** The CalcLengthPercentage::resolve method (line ~991) performs calculations like basis.px() * percentage without overflow checks, which can produce infinity or NaN values.\n\n3. **FFI Bridge to C++ (servo/ports/geckolib/glue.rs):** The Servo_ResolveCalcLengthPercentage function passes resolved values back to C++ code without validating for infinity or NaN.\n\n4. **Transform Processing (layout/style/nsStyleTransformMatrix.cpp):** The ProcessScaleHelper function and related transform functions use these unvalidated extreme values in matrix multiplication operations (via Matrix4x4::PreScale and operator*), where infinity values can cause crashes or undefined behavior in gfx/2d/Matrix.h.\n\nThe C++ in